But of course, the sine of any interval can be calculated to any required degree of accuracy.

This great fact of the incommensurability of musical inter- vals was known to the Greeks. It was recognized to be true both practically and theoretically. The eleventh chapter of the first book of Ptolemy's Haemonios contains first a mathe- matical demonstration that six Tones exceed an Octavo, and the amount of this excess, it is then stated, is pereeptihle eveo to the eor. Earlier writers than Ptolemy prove mathematically that six Tones exceed an Octave by an interval (called the Pythagorean Comma) whose ratio is talasa ε 531,441. Since this excess is slightly larger than the Comma cf Didymus (80 ε 81) which is the differenoe between the Major and the Minor Whole-tone (or between the true or just Major-third and the Pythagorean Major-third), Ptolemy's statement is not in the least incredible. All the difficulties sought to be obvi- ated by the device of equal temperament arise from small intervals, which are rarely larger than the Comma (80 r 81) by even a quarter of its aize. If such intervals are felt by moderas, we cannot deny to the ancients ability to perceive small intervals of the same sine. The existence ,of Quarter· tones at one period, at least, in the development of Greek music, points to a high degree of cultivation among the ancients of the feeling for pitch-differences.
